In statistics, the matrix normal distribution or matrix Gaussian distribution is a probability distribution that is a generalization of the multivariate normal distribution to matrix-valued random variables.

== Definition ==
The probability density function for the random matrix X (&quot;n&quot; × &quot;p&quot;) that follows the matrix normal distribution formula_4 has the form:

:formula_5

where formula_6 denotes trace and M is &quot;n&quot; × &quot;p&quot;, U is &quot;n&quot; × &quot;n&quot; and V is &quot;p&quot; × &quot;p&quot;, and the density is understood as the probability density function with respect to the standard Lebesgue measure in formula_7, i.e.: the measure corresponding to integration with respect to formula_8.

The matrix normal is related to the multivariate normal distribution in the following way:

:formula_9

if and only if

:formula_10

where formula_11 denotes the Kronecker product and formula_12 denotes the vectorization of formula_1.

